<TITLE>Fuchsia Dunlop</TITLE>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="1" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Fuchsia Dunlop</REFEX></REF>
 is an English writer and chef 
<REF MENTION="2" SYNFUNC="subj_rel-clause" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">who</REFEX></REF>
 specialises in Chinese cuisine. 
<REF MENTION="3" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">she</REFEX></REF>
 was an East Asian analyst at the BBC World Service and 
<REF MENTION="4" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="no_case" REG08-TYPE="empty" ENTITY="0">_</REFEX></REF>
 has three books to 
<REF MENTION="5" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">her</REFEX></REF>
 name, including the autobiography Shark's Fin and Sichuan Pepper. 
<REF MENTION="6" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">she</REFEX></REF>
 writes regularly on cooking and restaurants in China for Gourmet and Saveur, and for the Financial Times on such matters as Beijing's bid to translate into English the exotic names of many Chinese dishes. A fluent Mandarin speaker, 
<REF MENTION="7" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Dunlop</REFEX></REF>
 was the first occidental to train as a chef at the Sichuan Institute of Higher Cuisine in Chengdu, Sichuan, China. The author of Land of Plenty on Sichuan cuisine and Revolutionary Chinese Cookbook on Hunan cuisine, 
<REF MENTION="8" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Dunlop</REFEX></REF>
 has a considerable affection for Sichuan pepper.
</PARAGRAPH>
